metadata.name: Textura #97
metadata.description:
"Textura"

My initial goal was to create artwork that could trigger raw, visceral emotions and feelings. A polar opposite to the polite, clinical precision of some other collections, I wanted to embrace the grittier side of abstract art. 

This turned out to be a rather difficult project for me. It was a departure from my usual figurative / ink line style, where most of the time I find it straightforward to tell a "good" output from a "bad" one. Here, out of my comfort zone, I couldn't tell. I liked some outputs, I hated some. The ones I hated, usually would be someone else's favorites. Abstract art is hard !

After a while, some patterns started to emerge. The overall feedback was that, generally:
- blue outputs were peaceful
- orange ones were intense and aggressive
- black and white ones were oppressive and sometimes disturbing

If you can associate an emotion to any given output, I feel like I will have achieved my goal. Thank you to everyone who provided feedback !

 
Technically, this project also posed a number of challenges:
- how to blend a large number of procedural textures in a smooth, yet natural way
- how to make sure the final piece has some kind of depth, visible beyond the intricate layering
- how to optimize contrast and get vibrant results

This was mostly achieved by spending a lot of time designing and fine-tuning color schemes - enhanced versions of color palettes, that also contain pre and post-processing settings.

The collection features a total of 31 color schemes. 

Key commands:
'1', '2', '4': increase resolution
's': save png
'n': toggle background noise
'c': toggle background canvas texture

On mobile devices, the rendering resolution is reduced to deal with memory limitations.

metadata.name: Geode #18
metadata.description:
A single seed shape is chosen from 13, and placed onto the plane. At every step, a copy of this seed is laid edge-to-edge adjacent to an existing shape, without causing any overlaps. This copy is colored based on the edge it shares with the existing shape. The process continues until the animation completes.

New shapes are placed closest to a moving target. In some mints, this target is slow moving, causing new shapes to expand radially from the seed. In other mints, this target races around, causing new shapes to chase it. 

Each of the 13 shapes forms different patterns under different circumstances. Not all patterns will be explored.

Controls:
  - SPACE: Pause/unpause the animation.
  - ENTER: Skip the animation.
  - R: Restart the animation.

URL Params:
  - "preview=1": Skip the animation.
  - "flex=1": Adapt the boundaries to the size of the window.
  - “slow=1”: Draw only one shape per frame.

Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: Pearls #21
metadata.description:
Pearls is a generative minimal artwork made with 100% code in p5js.

This algorithm places perfectly round pearls into multiple stacked grids and connects them in a pleasing way. The small grids lead to interesting emerging patterns. Some see faces and fish, others see ancient hardware and elephants, and some just enjoy the minimal simplicity.

-- controls (in live view)
s: to save the current image
a: to play a small animation

-- some attributes
layout: 2x2 to 34x34
palette: genuary, monochrome red & purple, night
mode: ink, walk
bias: central, north, east, south, west
density: sparse, middle, dense
symmetry: none, vertical, horizontal, point
layer: 2 to 6

metadata.name: In Due Time #164
metadata.description:
“In Due Time” is a collaborative generative collection between artists Melissa Wiederrecht and Amber Vittoria. Inspired by Wiederrecht’s mastery of line and Vittoria’s notable palette, this 1/1/250 series captures the present moment. It serves as a reminder that we are more similar than we are different, leveraging homogeneous shapes to create distinctive compositions.

Vittoria’s poem for the collection:

“In Due Time”
We will all become
Particles dancing
Across the skyline.

The artwork listed is indeed authentic, created by, and copyright to artists Melissa Wiederrecht and Amber Vittoria; the purchase of this NFT is a purchase of the asset, not of the copyright.

-------------------------------------------

To save a high-resolution image for printing, click “open” under the image on the page for your token, and then hit:

Digits “1” through “9” to get an image that is 1000 through 9000px tall.  This may take a while, depending on the size and your computer, so please be patient.

metadata.name: Con(text)ual #86
metadata.description:
Con(text)ual is a generative painting made from ASCII characters confined into shapes. Shapes are randomly drawn onto the canvas, then filled with individual characters from a character array. The density of characters is dependent upon the size of the shape, creating some transparencies and an organic feel to each shape.

I've long been interested in typography as an artform and this is an extension of my typography explorations.

There are a total of 10 color pallets. The number of shapes on each canvas varies from 3 to 9. The edition size was chosen based on the code, which lends itself well to a wide array of potential outcomes. Please get in touch with me if you want a larger resolution size for printing. 

I hope you enjoy the art!

Made with 100% Code and p5.js
Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0
